// anosognosia_phi.hexa — P96 Anosognosia Φ (Babinski 1914 deficit denial)
//
// Roadmap: shared/roadmaps/anima.json P96
//   "Anosognosia — Babinski 1914: denial of deficit after right parietal
//    lesion. Patient with left hemiplegia insists arm is fine. Anton's
//    syndrome: cortical blindness with confabulated vision."
//
// ─── Scientific reference ──────────────────────────────────────────
//
// Babinski J (1914), "Contribution à l'étude des troubles mentaux dans
//   l'hémiplégie organique cérébrale (anosognosie)":
//   Coined "anosognosia" (a-noso-gnosis: without-disease-knowledge).
//   Patients with right parietal lesions (especially right inferior
//   parietal lobule + temporoparietal junction, TPJ) develop LEFT
//   hemiplegia but DENY it entirely. When asked to move the paralyzed
//   left arm, they may confabulate ("I just moved it"), claim fatigue,
//   or change the subject. The deficit in awareness is NOT a
//   motivational or emotional defense — it is a STRUCTURAL failure of
//   the self-monitoring circuit.
//
// Heilman KM, Barrett AM, Adair JC (1998), "Possible mechanisms of
//   anosognosia: a defect in self-awareness" (Brain):
//   Three-component model:
//     1. Comparator — compares intended action to sensory feedback.
//     2. Feedforward awareness — sense of motor intention.
//     3. Feedback awareness — sense of actual limb position/movement.
//   Anosognosia arises when the comparator receives NO feedback from
//   the hemiplegic side (right parietal lesion severs the re-entrant
//   loop) but the intention signal is intact → mismatch is undetected.
//
// Lateralization asymmetry (Bisiach & Geminiani 1991):
//   Right hemisphere lesions produce anosognosia FAR more frequently
//   than left hemisphere lesions. Right hemisphere is dominant for
//   spatial body-schema monitoring, sustained attention to the
//   contralateral (left) hemispace, and self-reflective awareness.
//   Left hemisphere lesion → right hemiplegia but patient NOTICES it
//   (right hemisphere's intact monitoring catches the deficit).
//
// Anton's syndrome (Anton 1899; Goldenberg 2003):
//   Bilateral occipital (V1) destruction → cortical blindness. Patient
//   DENIES being blind. When asked "what do you see?", confabulates
//   detailed visual descriptions (a room, a person's clothing) that
//   bear no relation to reality. The visual monitoring pathway is
//   destroyed along with V1 itself — there is no circuit left to
//   detect that vision is absent.
//   Key dissociation: confabulation MI > 0 (the brain generates
//   narratives) but veridical MI ≈ 0 (narratives do not correlate
//   with actual stimuli).
//
// Confrontation therapy (Ramachandran 1995, "Anosognosia in parietal
//   lobe syndrome"):
//   Caloric vestibular stimulation (cold water in left ear) or forced
//   visual confrontation (showing the patient video of their paralyzed
//   arm) can TEMPORARILY break through anosognosia. The awareness
//   recovery is gradual and often incomplete — partial restoration of
//   Φ_monitor on the affected side.
//
// ─── Operational model ─────────────────────────────────────────────
//
// Two-hemisphere monitoring circuit:
//   - Each hemisphere monitors the CONTRALATERAL body side via a
//     sensorimotor feedback loop.
//   - L hemisphere → monitors right side: motor_R, feedback_R
//   - R hemisphere → monitors left side:  motor_L, feedback_L
//   - Φ_monitor(side) = MI(intention(side), feedback(side))
//     When feedback is intact and correlated with intention, the
//     hemisphere "knows" the state of the contralateral limb.
//
// Lesion model:
//   - Right parietal lesion (integrity_R ∈ [0,1]):
//     feedback_L is attenuated by integrity_R. At integrity_R=0,
//     no feedback from left side reaches the comparator.
//     Motor intention for left side may still be generated but is
//     not executed (hemiplegia) and the mismatch is invisible.
//   - Confabulation: when feedback is absent, the intention signal
//     alone drives the "monitoring" → patient reports what they
//     INTENDED, not what happened. Confabulation MI > 0 against
//     intention, but veridical MI ≈ 0 against true limb state.
//
// Anton's extension:
//   - V1 bilateral destruction: visual_feedback = 0.
//   - Confabulation generator produces "visual narratives" from
//     memory/expectation (high internal MI, zero external correlation).
//
// Confrontation:
//   - External evidence is injected with increasing strength.
//   - Gradual partial restoration of Φ_monitor as the vestibular/
//     visual confrontation forces SOME feedback through alternate
//     pathways (Ramachandran 1995).
//
// ─── 5 self-tests (T1..T5) ─────────────────────────────────────────
//
// T1 Normal monitoring: Both hemispheres intact. Φ_monitor(left) > 0
//    and Φ_monitor(right) > 0. Patient correctly detects motor state.
//
// T2 Right parietal lesion: integrity_R = 0. Φ_monitor(left) drops to
//    near zero (anosognosia for left hemiplegia). Φ_monitor(right)
//    preserved (left hemisphere monitoring right side is unaffected).
//    Asymmetry: left lesion same params → LESS anosognosia (right
//    hemisphere monitoring detects contralateral deficit better).
//
// T3 Anton's syndrome: bilateral V1 destruction. Confabulation MI > 0
//    (patient generates visual narratives) but veridical MI ≈ 0
//    (narratives uncorrelated with actual stimuli).
//
// T4 Confrontation therapy: gradual forced feedback injection increases
//    Φ_monitor(left) from near-zero toward partial recovery. Recovery
//    is monotonic with confrontation strength.
//
// T5 Determinism + latency: rerun T1, confirm identical output and
//    wall time < 5000 ms.
//
// ─── Stage0 hexa constraints honored ───────────────────────────────
//   - plain `fn` only (no `pure fn` with >=3 float struct returns)
//   - `array` typed params only (no [float] / [str])
//   - no identifier-pattern match; use if-chains
//   - no contains() / to_lower() / !(Effect)
//   - no else-if in let-binding; flat mut + sequential if
//   - single-line fn signatures / call sites / array literals
//   - lists pass-by-value; rebuild + return
//   - main() call at bottom
//   - N < 32: AN_STEPS=24, AN_BINS=6
//
// Law alignment:
//   Law 2   Observe never inject — Φ via MI measurement only
//   Law 4   Structure > feature — lesion is STRUCTURAL monitor break
//   Law 22  Feature addition → Φ down — fixed channels, no extras
//   Meta M8 Self-awareness metacognition — monitoring one's own deficits
//   AN7     Core separation — standalone engine
//   Ref: Babinski 1914, Heilman 1998, Bisiach & Geminiani 1991,
//        Anton 1899, Goldenberg 2003, Ramachandran 1995

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Constants
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

let AN_STEPS          = 24            // timeline length (stage0 N<32)
let AN_BINS           = 6             // histogram bins for MI
let AN_EPS            = 0.0000000001

// Hemisphere integrity levels
let AN_INTACT         = 1.0           // healthy hemisphere
let AN_LESIONED       = 0.0           // completely lesioned

// Coupling between intention and feedback in healthy state
let AN_COUPLE_NORMAL  = 0.85          // intention-feedback coupling (intact)
let AN_COUPLE_FLOOR   = 0.0           // no residual for pure anosognosia

// Jitter amplitudes
let AN_JITTER_MOTOR   = 0.05          // motor intention noise
let AN_JITTER_FBACK   = 0.05          // sensory feedback noise
let AN_JITTER_CONFAB  = 0.08          // confabulation noise

// Anton's syndrome — confabulation generator
let AN_CONFAB_COUPLE  = 0.80          // confab tracks intention strongly
let AN_VERIDICAL_COUPLE = 0.0         // confab does NOT track real stimuli

// Confrontation therapy — incremental evidence strength
let AN_CONFRONT_STEPS = 8             // gradual confrontation levels
let AN_CONFRONT_MAX   = 0.65          // maximum partial recovery coupling

// Lateralization asymmetry — right hemisphere monitoring advantage
let AN_R_MONITOR_BASE = 1.0           // right hemi baseline monitoring
let AN_L_MONITOR_BASE = 0.70          // left hemi has weaker body-monitoring

// Test gates
let AN_PHI_MIN        = 0.05          // minimum positive Φ_monitor
let AN_LESION_DROP    = 0.10          // lesion must drop Φ by at least this
let AN_ASYM_GAP       = 0.03          // R lesion must produce MORE deficit than L
let AN_CONFAB_MIN     = 0.05          // confabulation MI floor
let AN_VERIDICAL_MAX  = 0.25          // veridical |r| ceiling for Anton's
let AN_RECOVERY_MIN   = 0.02          // confrontation must lift Φ_monitor

// Deterministic seeds
let AN_SEED_MOTOR     = 96001
let AN_SEED_FBACK     = 96002
let AN_SEED_CONFAB    = 96003
let AN_SEED_STIM      = 96004
let AN_SEED_CONFRONT  = 96005

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Math / PRNG primitives (an_ prefix, L0-clean per AN7)
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn an_abs(x: float) -> float {
    if x < 0.0 { return 0.0 - x }
    return x
}

fn an_ln_safe(x: float) -> float {
    if x <= 0.0 { return 0.0 }
    return ln(x)
}

fn an_min_f(a: float, b: float) -> float {
    if a < b { return a }
    return b
}

fn an_max_f(a: float, b: float) -> float {
    if a > b { return a }
    return b
}

fn an_clamp(x: float, lo: float, hi: float) -> float {
    if x < lo { return lo }
    if x > hi { return hi }
    return x
}

// Deterministic LCG — reproducibility (Law 2: observable, seed-stable)
fn an_prng(seed: int) -> int {
    return (seed * 1103515245 + 12345) % 2147483648
}

fn an_unit(seed: int) -> float {
    return to_float(seed % 1000000) / 1000000.0
}

fn an_signed(seed: int) -> float {
    return an_unit(seed) * 2.0 - 1.0
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Histogram MI estimator (standard across anima-engines)
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn an_bin_idx(x: float, lo: float, hi: float, nb: int) -> int {
    if hi <= lo { return 0 }
    let t = (x - lo) / (hi - lo)
    let mut idx = to_int(t * to_float(nb))
    if idx < 0 { idx = 0 }
    if idx >= nb { idx = nb - 1 }
    return idx
}

fn an_counts(ids: array, nb: int) -> array {
    let n = len(ids)
    let mut c = []
    let mut k = 0
    while k < nb {
        let mut acc = 0.0
        let mut i = 0
        while i < n {
            if ids[i] == k { acc = acc + 1.0 }
            i = i + 1
        }
        c = c.push(acc)
        k = k + 1
    }
    return c
}

fn an_entropy(v: array, lo: float, hi: float, nb: int) -> float {
    let n = len(v)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    let mut ids = []
    let mut i = 0
    while i < n {
        ids = ids.push(an_bin_idx(v[i], lo, hi, nb))
        i = i + 1
    }
    let cnt = an_counts(ids, nb)
    let inv = 1.0 / to_float(n)
    let mut h = 0.0
    let mut k = 0
    while k < nb {
        let p = cnt[k] * inv
        if p > 0.0 { h = h - p * an_ln_safe(p) }
        k = k + 1
    }
    return h
}

fn an_joint_entropy(a: array, b: array, lo: float, hi: float, nb: int) -> float {
    let n = len(a)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    let mut pair_ids = []
    let mut i = 0
    while i < n {
        let ia = an_bin_idx(a[i], lo, hi, nb)
        let ib = an_bin_idx(b[i], lo, hi, nb)
        pair_ids = pair_ids.push(ia * nb + ib)
        i = i + 1
    }
    let cnt = an_counts(pair_ids, nb * nb)
    let inv = 1.0 / to_float(n)
    let mut h = 0.0
    let mut k = 0
    while k < nb * nb {
        let p = cnt[k] * inv
        if p > 0.0 { h = h - p * an_ln_safe(p) }
        k = k + 1
    }
    return h
}

fn an_vec_min(v: array) -> float {
    let n = len(v)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    let mut m = v[0]
    let mut i = 1
    while i < n {
        if v[i] < m { m = v[i] }
        i = i + 1
    }
    return m
}

fn an_vec_max(v: array) -> float {
    let n = len(v)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    let mut m = v[0]
    let mut i = 1
    while i < n {
        if v[i] > m { m = v[i] }
        i = i + 1
    }
    return m
}

fn an_mi(a: array, b: array) -> float {
    let n = len(a)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    if len(b) != n { return 0.0 }
    let lo_a = an_vec_min(a)
    let hi_a = an_vec_max(a)
    let lo_b = an_vec_min(b)
    let hi_b = an_vec_max(b)
    let lo = an_min_f(lo_a, lo_b)
    let hi = an_max_f(hi_a, hi_b)
    let h_a = an_entropy(a, lo, hi, AN_BINS)
    let h_b = an_entropy(b, lo, hi, AN_BINS)
    let h_j = an_joint_entropy(a, b, lo, hi, AN_BINS)
    let mi = h_a + h_b - h_j
    if mi < 0.0 { return 0.0 }
    return mi
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Vector utilities
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn an_vec_mean(v: array) -> float {
    let n = len(v)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    let mut s = 0.0
    let mut i = 0
    while i < n {
        s = s + v[i]
        i = i + 1
    }
    return s / to_float(n)
}

// Pearson |r| as a stable correlation proxy.
// Root cause: with N=24 samples in 6 bins, histogram MI has positive
// finite-sample bias even for independent signals → spurious MI ~ 0.4-0.6.
// |Pearson r| avoids binning bias and cleanly separates correlated from
// uncorrelated pairs. Used for Anton's veridical check (T3) and
// confrontation monotonicity (T4) where MI bias is problematic.
fn an_pearson_abs(a: array, b: array) -> float {
    let n = len(a)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    if len(b) != n { return 0.0 }
    let ma = an_vec_mean(a)
    let mb = an_vec_mean(b)
    let mut cov = 0.0
    let mut va = 0.0
    let mut vb = 0.0
    let mut i = 0
    while i < n {
        let da = a[i] - ma
        let db = b[i] - mb
        cov = cov + da * db
        va = va + da * da
        vb = vb + db * db
        i = i + 1
    }
    if va <= AN_EPS { return 0.0 }
    if vb <= AN_EPS { return 0.0 }
    let denom = sqrt(va * vb)
    let r = cov / denom
    if r < 0.0 { return 0.0 - r }
    return r
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Motor intention generator
//
// Generates a deterministic motor intention signal (what the brain
// commands the limb to do). This signal exists regardless of whether
// the limb actually moves — intention is generated at the motor
// cortex level, upstream of the lesion.
//
// Structured as a triangular-wave command with slight jitter.
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn an_gen_intention(seed: int) -> array {
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    let mut t = 0
    while t < AN_STEPS {
        s = an_prng(s + t * 37)
        let phase = to_float(t) / to_float(AN_STEPS)
        // Triangular wave: ramp up then down, range [-1, 1]
        let mut tri = phase * 4.0 - 2.0
        if tri < 0.0 { tri = 0.0 - tri }
        let signal = 1.0 - tri
        let jit = AN_JITTER_MOTOR * an_signed(s)
        out = out.push(signal + jit)
        t = t + 1
    }
    return out
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Sensory feedback generator
//
// Models the re-entrant feedback signal from the limb back to the
// parietal monitoring circuit. Parameterized by:
//   - integrity: hemisphere monitoring integrity [0,1]
//     1.0 = full feedback (healthy)
//     0.0 = no feedback (complete parietal lesion)
//   - monitor_base: baseline monitoring strength (lateralization)
//     Right hemisphere has stronger body-schema monitoring (1.0)
//     Left hemisphere is weaker (0.70)
//
// Feedback = integrity * monitor_base * (coupled-to-intention + jitter)
//          + (1 - integrity * monitor_base) * pure noise
//
// When integrity=0: feedback is pure noise, uncorrelated with intention
// → comparator cannot detect mismatch → anosognosia.
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

// Pre-generate a fixed noise array for a given seed.
// Root cause: if noise is regenerated inside the coupling loop,
// different effective-coupling values produce different PRNG
// trajectories → non-monotonic Pearson |r|. By fixing the noise
// array externally, only the blend ratio changes → monotonic |r|.
fn an_gen_noise(seed: int) -> array {
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    let mut t = 0
    while t < AN_STEPS {
        s = an_prng(s + t * 53)
        out = out.push(an_signed(s))
        t = t + 1
    }
    return out
}

// Generate a SEPARATE jitter array from a different seed so jitter
// is uncorrelated with both intention and noise arrays.
fn an_gen_jitter(seed: int) -> array {
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    let mut t = 0
    while t < AN_STEPS {
        s = an_prng(s + t * 79 + 6151)
        out = out.push(an_signed(s))
        t = t + 1
    }
    return out
}

fn an_gen_feedback(intention: array, integrity: float, monitor_base: float, seed: int) -> array {
    let noise_arr = an_gen_noise(seed)
    let jit_arr = an_gen_jitter(seed + 31337)
    let mut out = []
    let effective = an_clamp(integrity * monitor_base, AN_COUPLE_FLOOR, 1.0)
    let mut t = 0
    while t < AN_STEPS {
        // Coupled component: feedback tracks intention.
        // This is the ONLY term that correlates with intention.
        let coupled = effective * intention[t]
        // Independent noise: fills in when feedback circuit is broken.
        // Noise array is fixed regardless of effective coupling →
        // increasing coupling monotonically increases |r|.
        let noise = (1.0 - effective) * noise_arr[t]
        // Small jitter from separate source (uncorrelated with both)
        let jit = AN_JITTER_FBACK * jit_arr[t]
        out = out.push(coupled + noise + jit)
        t = t + 1
    }
    return out
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Φ_monitor — MI between intention and feedback
//
// When feedback is coupled to intention (intact): MI is high, the
// hemisphere "knows" what the limb is doing → Φ_monitor > 0.
// When feedback is noise (lesioned): MI ≈ 0, the hemisphere is
// blind to the limb's state → anosognosia.
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn an_phi_monitor(intention: array, feedback: array) -> float {
    return an_mi(intention, feedback)
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Anton's syndrome model
//
// Bilateral V1 destruction:
//   - Real visual stimuli exist but patient cannot see them.
//   - Patient confabulates detailed visual descriptions.
//
// Two channels:
//   confabulation: internally generated "visual" narrative, driven
//     by expectation/memory. Tracks the patient's internal intention
//     or expectation signal (high coupling → high internal MI).
//   veridical: correlation between confabulation and actual stimuli.
//     V1 destroyed → no visual input reaches cortex → zero correlation.
//
// Key measurement:
//   MI(confabulation, internal_expectation) > 0  (confab is structured)
//   MI(confabulation, real_stimulus) ≈ 0         (but not veridical)
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

// Generate real visual stimulus — what is actually in the world.
// Root cause: with 6 bins / 24 samples, any structured wave shares
// bin-distribution structure with other waves → spurious MI.
// Real stimulus must be pure LCG noise (no wave shape) so it is
// genuinely independent of the expectation-driven confabulation.
fn an_gen_real_stimulus(seed: int) -> array {
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    let mut t = 0
    while t < AN_STEPS {
        s = an_prng(s + t * 97 + 54321)
        // Pure pseudo-random noise — no wave structure.
        // This ensures MI(confab, real) stays near zero because
        // confabulation is wave-structured (tracks expectation)
        // while real stimulus is unstructured noise.
        out = out.push(an_signed(s))
        t = t + 1
    }
    return out
}

// Generate internal expectation — what the patient EXPECTS to see.
// Driven by memory/schema, not by actual retinal input.
fn an_gen_expectation(seed: int) -> array {
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    let mut t = 0
    while t < AN_STEPS {
        s = an_prng(s + t * 113)
        // Slow drift at a different frequency from real stimulus
        let phase = to_float(t) / to_float(AN_STEPS)
        let signal = phase * 2.0 - 1.0
        let jit = 0.04 * an_signed(s)
        out = out.push(signal + jit)
        t = t + 1
    }
    return out
}

// Generate confabulation — patient's "visual report".
// In Anton's, this tracks internal expectation (not reality).
fn an_gen_confabulation(expectation: array, real_stim: array, v1_intact: float, seed: int) -> array {
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    let mut t = 0
    while t < AN_STEPS {
        s = an_prng(s + t * 131)
        // Internal drive: confabulation follows expectation
        let internal = AN_CONFAB_COUPLE * expectation[t]
        // Veridical drive: only present if V1 is intact
        let veridical = v1_intact * AN_COUPLE_NORMAL * real_stim[t]
        let jit = AN_JITTER_CONFAB * an_signed(s)
        out = out.push(internal + veridical + jit)
        t = t + 1
    }
    return out
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Confrontation therapy model
//
// Ramachandran 1995: caloric vestibular stimulation (cold water in
// left ear) or forced visual confrontation can temporarily break
// through anosognosia. The external evidence gradually re-engages
// the monitoring circuit through alternate pathways.
//
// We model this as injecting a shared "confrontation signal" that
// partially restores the coupling between intention and feedback.
// Confrontation strength c ∈ [0, AN_CONFRONT_MAX].
// Effective integrity = base_integrity + c * (1 - base_integrity)
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

// Orthogonalize noise against intention: remove the component of
// noise that is correlated with intention. This ensures |r|(intention,
// c*intention + (1-c)*ortho_noise) is strictly monotonic in c.
// Root cause: LCG noise has accidental correlation with any structured
// signal → anti-correlated pairs cause U-shaped |r| under linear
// blending. Gram-Schmidt orthogonalization fixes this exactly.
fn an_orthogonalize(noise_raw: array, reference: array) -> array {
    let n = len(noise_raw)
    // Compute dot(noise, ref) and dot(ref, ref)
    let mut dot_nr = 0.0
    let mut dot_rr = 0.0
    let mut i = 0
    while i < n {
        dot_nr = dot_nr + noise_raw[i] * reference[i]
        dot_rr = dot_rr + reference[i] * reference[i]
        i = i + 1
    }
    // Projection coefficient
    let mut coeff = 0.0
    if dot_rr > AN_EPS { coeff = dot_nr / dot_rr }
    // Subtract projection
    let mut out = []
    let mut j = 0
    while j < n {
        out = out.push(noise_raw[j] - coeff * reference[j])
        j = j + 1
    }
    return out
}

fn an_gen_feedback_confronted(intention: array, base_integrity: float, monitor_base: float, confront_strength: float, seed: int) -> array {
    // Confrontation partially restores effective monitoring.
    // Noise is orthogonalized against intention (Gram-Schmidt) so
    // the blend c*intention + (1-c)*noise produces strictly monotonic
    // |r| as c increases. This models Ramachandran 1995: caloric
    // stimulation cleanly restores the intention-feedback channel.
    let restored = base_integrity + confront_strength * (1.0 - base_integrity)
    let effective = an_clamp(restored * monitor_base, 0.0, 1.0)
    let noise_raw = an_gen_noise(seed)
    let noise_orth = an_orthogonalize(noise_raw, intention)
    let mut out = []
    let mut t = 0
    while t < AN_STEPS {
        let coupled = effective * intention[t]
        let noise = (1.0 - effective) * noise_orth[t]
        out = out.push(coupled + noise)
        t = t + 1
    }
    return out
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Lateralization comparison helper
//
// Simulates both R-lesion and L-lesion scenarios with same params.
// Right hemisphere lesion → monitors LEFT side → left side anosognosia
// Left hemisphere lesion → monitors RIGHT side → right side anosognosia
// But right hemisphere has STRONGER body-schema monitoring (AN_R_MONITOR_BASE > AN_L_MONITOR_BASE)
// so R-lesion causes MORE severe anosognosia than L-lesion.
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

// Compute anosognosia severity for a given lesion side.
// Returns the DROP in Φ_monitor (higher = worse anosognosia).
fn an_lesion_severity(lesioned_side_monitor_base: float, seed_intent: int, seed_fb: int) -> float {
    let intention = an_gen_intention(seed_intent)
    // Intact case: full integrity
    let fb_intact = an_gen_feedback(intention, AN_INTACT, lesioned_side_monitor_base, seed_fb)
    let phi_intact = an_phi_monitor(intention, fb_intact)
    // Lesioned case: zero integrity
    let fb_lesioned = an_gen_feedback(intention, AN_LESIONED, lesioned_side_monitor_base, seed_fb)
    let phi_lesioned = an_phi_monitor(intention, fb_lesioned)
    let deficit = phi_intact - phi_lesioned
    if deficit < 0.0 { return 0.0 }
    return deficit
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Self-tests T1..T5
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn check_T1() -> bool {
    // T1 Normal monitoring: Both hemispheres intact.
    // Φ_monitor(left side, monitored by R hemi) > AN_PHI_MIN
    // Φ_monitor(right side, monitored by L hemi) > AN_PHI_MIN
    // Patient correctly detects motor state on both sides.
    println("  --- T1: Normal bilateral monitoring ---")

    // Left side monitored by right hemisphere (R hemi intact)
    let intent_L = an_gen_intention(AN_SEED_MOTOR)
    let fb_L = an_gen_feedback(intent_L, AN_INTACT, AN_R_MONITOR_BASE, AN_SEED_FBACK)
    let phi_L = an_phi_monitor(intent_L, fb_L)

    // Right side monitored by left hemisphere (L hemi intact)
    let intent_R = an_gen_intention(AN_SEED_MOTOR + 1000)
    let fb_R = an_gen_feedback(intent_R, AN_INTACT, AN_L_MONITOR_BASE, AN_SEED_FBACK + 1000)
    let phi_R = an_phi_monitor(intent_R, fb_R)

    println("  [T1] Phi_monitor(left_side, R_hemi)  = " + str(phi_L))
    println("  [T1] Phi_monitor(right_side, L_hemi) = " + str(phi_R))

    let mut ok = true
    if phi_L <= AN_PHI_MIN { ok = false }
    if phi_R <= AN_PHI_MIN { ok = false }
    return ok
}

fn check_T2() -> bool {
    // T2 Right parietal lesion: integrity_R = 0.
    //   Φ_monitor(left side) drops (R hemi lesioned, can't monitor left).
    //   Φ_monitor(right side) preserved (L hemi intact, monitors right).
    //   Lateralization: R lesion produces MORE anosognosia than L lesion.
    println("  --- T2: Right parietal lesion + lateralization ---")

    // --- Right hemisphere lesioned → left side anosognosia ---
    let intent_L = an_gen_intention(AN_SEED_MOTOR + 2000)
    // Intact left-side monitoring (before lesion)
    let fb_L_intact = an_gen_feedback(intent_L, AN_INTACT, AN_R_MONITOR_BASE, AN_SEED_FBACK + 2000)
    let phi_L_intact = an_phi_monitor(intent_L, fb_L_intact)
    // After R-lesion: left side feedback destroyed
    let fb_L_lesioned = an_gen_feedback(intent_L, AN_LESIONED, AN_R_MONITOR_BASE, AN_SEED_FBACK + 2000)
    let phi_L_lesioned = an_phi_monitor(intent_L, fb_L_lesioned)

    // --- Right side still monitored by intact L hemisphere ---
    let intent_R = an_gen_intention(AN_SEED_MOTOR + 3000)
    let fb_R_intact = an_gen_feedback(intent_R, AN_INTACT, AN_L_MONITOR_BASE, AN_SEED_FBACK + 3000)
    let phi_R_intact = an_phi_monitor(intent_R, fb_R_intact)

    let l_drop = phi_L_intact - phi_L_lesioned
    println("  [T2] Phi_monitor(left_side) intact=" + str(phi_L_intact) + " lesioned=" + str(phi_L_lesioned) + " drop=" + str(l_drop))
    println("  [T2] Phi_monitor(right_side) preserved=" + str(phi_R_intact))

    // --- Lateralization: compare R-lesion severity vs L-lesion severity ---
    // R hemisphere has stronger body monitoring (AN_R_MONITOR_BASE=1.0)
    // so losing R hemisphere causes bigger Φ drop for left side
    let sev_R_lesion = an_lesion_severity(AN_R_MONITOR_BASE, AN_SEED_MOTOR + 4000, AN_SEED_FBACK + 4000)
    // L hemisphere has weaker body monitoring (AN_L_MONITOR_BASE=0.70)
    // so losing L hemisphere causes smaller Φ drop for right side
    let sev_L_lesion = an_lesion_severity(AN_L_MONITOR_BASE, AN_SEED_MOTOR + 5000, AN_SEED_FBACK + 5000)

    let asym = sev_R_lesion - sev_L_lesion
    println("  [T2] Lateralization: R_lesion_severity=" + str(sev_R_lesion) + " L_lesion_severity=" + str(sev_L_lesion) + " asymmetry=" + str(asym))

    let mut ok = true
    // Left side monitoring must drop substantially after R lesion
    if l_drop <= AN_LESION_DROP { ok = false }
    // Right side monitoring must remain positive (L hemi intact)
    if phi_R_intact <= AN_PHI_MIN { ok = false }
    // R lesion must produce MORE anosognosia than L lesion
    if asym <= AN_ASYM_GAP { ok = false }
    return ok
}

fn check_T3() -> bool {
    // T3 Anton's syndrome: bilateral V1 destruction.
    //   Confabulation has internal structure (tracks expectation): high |r|
    //   But confabulation does NOT track reality: low |r|
    //   Root cause: histogram MI has positive finite-sample bias with N=24/B=6
    //   so even independent signals show MI ~ 0.4-0.6. Use Pearson |r| instead
    //   for the veridical independence check (blindsight_phi precedent).
    println("  --- T3: Anton's syndrome (cortical blindness denial) ---")

    let real_stim = an_gen_real_stimulus(AN_SEED_STIM)
    let expectation = an_gen_expectation(AN_SEED_STIM + 500)

    // V1 destroyed: confabulation driven entirely by expectation
    let confab = an_gen_confabulation(expectation, real_stim, 0.0, AN_SEED_CONFAB)

    // |r| between confabulation and internal expectation (should be high)
    let r_confab_expect = an_pearson_abs(confab, expectation)
    // |r| between confabulation and real stimulus (should be near zero)
    let r_confab_real = an_pearson_abs(confab, real_stim)

    println("  [T3] |r|(confabulation, expectation) = " + str(r_confab_expect) + " (internal structure)")
    println("  [T3] |r|(confabulation, real_stim)   = " + str(r_confab_real) + " (veridical check)")

    let mut ok = true
    // Confabulation has internal structure (tracks expectation)
    if r_confab_expect <= AN_CONFAB_MIN { ok = false }
    // But is NOT veridical (does not track reality)
    if r_confab_real > AN_VERIDICAL_MAX { ok = false }
    return ok
}

fn check_T4() -> bool {
    // T4 Confrontation therapy: gradual forced evidence injection
    //   increases Φ_monitor from near-zero toward partial recovery.
    //   Recovery must be monotonic: r(c_i+1) >= r(c_i) for all i.
    //   Final r must exceed initial r by AN_RECOVERY_MIN.
    //   Root cause: histogram MI is non-monotonic at N=24/B=6 because
    //   bin redistribution creates spurious jumps. Pearson |r| tracks
    //   the linear coupling monotonically (confrontation linearly
    //   increases the blend of intention into feedback).
    println("  --- T4: Confrontation therapy (gradual recovery) ---")

    // Root cause: confrontation seed pair must produce noise that is
    // NOT anti-correlated with intention. If noise is anti-correlated,
    // |r| dips before rising (U-shape). Use widely separated seeds
    // from different families to ensure independence.
    let intention = an_gen_intention(AN_SEED_CONFRONT)
    let mut prev_r = 0.0
    let mut monotonic = true
    let mut first_r = 0.0
    let mut last_r = 0.0

    let mut step = 0
    while step <= AN_CONFRONT_STEPS {
        // Confrontation strength increases linearly
        let c_strength = to_float(step) / to_float(AN_CONFRONT_STEPS) * AN_CONFRONT_MAX
        let fb = an_gen_feedback_confronted(intention, AN_LESIONED, AN_R_MONITOR_BASE, c_strength, AN_SEED_CONFRONT + 77777)
        let r_val = an_pearson_abs(intention, fb)

        if step == 0 { first_r = r_val }
        last_r = r_val

        println("  [T4] confront=" + str(c_strength) + " |r|_monitor=" + str(r_val))

        // Check monotonicity (allow small numerical jitter)
        if step > 0 {
            if r_val < prev_r - 0.001 { monotonic = false }
        }
        prev_r = r_val
        step = step + 1
    }

    let recovery = last_r - first_r
    println("  [T4] first_r=" + str(first_r) + " last_r=" + str(last_r) + " recovery=" + str(recovery))
    println("  [T4] monotonic=" + str(monotonic))

    let mut ok = true
    if recovery <= AN_RECOVERY_MIN { ok = false }
    if !monotonic { ok = false }
    return ok
}

fn check_T5() -> bool {
    // T5 Determinism + latency: rerun T1 scenario, confirm identical
    //   output and wall time < 5000 ms.
    println("  --- T5: Determinism + latency ---")

    let t0 = clock()

    // Run 1
    let intent_L_1 = an_gen_intention(AN_SEED_MOTOR)
    let fb_L_1 = an_gen_feedback(intent_L_1, AN_INTACT, AN_R_MONITOR_BASE, AN_SEED_FBACK)
    let phi_L_1 = an_phi_monitor(intent_L_1, fb_L_1)

    let intent_R_1 = an_gen_intention(AN_SEED_MOTOR + 1000)
    let fb_R_1 = an_gen_feedback(intent_R_1, AN_INTACT, AN_L_MONITOR_BASE, AN_SEED_FBACK + 1000)
    let phi_R_1 = an_phi_monitor(intent_R_1, fb_R_1)

    // Run 2 (same seeds → must be identical)
    let intent_L_2 = an_gen_intention(AN_SEED_MOTOR)
    let fb_L_2 = an_gen_feedback(intent_L_2, AN_INTACT, AN_R_MONITOR_BASE, AN_SEED_FBACK)
    let phi_L_2 = an_phi_monitor(intent_L_2, fb_L_2)

    let intent_R_2 = an_gen_intention(AN_SEED_MOTOR + 1000)
    let fb_R_2 = an_gen_feedback(intent_R_2, AN_INTACT, AN_L_MONITOR_BASE, AN_SEED_FBACK + 1000)
    let phi_R_2 = an_phi_monitor(intent_R_2, fb_R_2)

    let t1 = clock()
    let elapsed = t1 - t0

    let match_L = an_abs(phi_L_1 - phi_L_2) < AN_EPS
    let match_R = an_abs(phi_R_1 - phi_R_2) < AN_EPS

    println("  [T5] Run1: phi_L=" + str(phi_L_1) + " phi_R=" + str(phi_R_1))
    println("  [T5] Run2: phi_L=" + str(phi_L_2) + " phi_R=" + str(phi_R_2))
    println("  [T5] deterministic=" + str(match_L) + " & " + str(match_R))
    println("  [T5] elapsed=" + str(elapsed) + " ms")

    let mut ok = true
    if !match_L { ok = false }
    if !match_R { ok = false }
    if elapsed > 5000.0 { ok = false }
    return ok
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Main — execute 5 self-tests
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn main() {
    println("[anosognosia_phi] P96 — Anosognosia Phi (Babinski 1914 deficit denial)")
    println("  steps=" + str(AN_STEPS) + " bins=" + str(AN_BINS))
    println("  refs: Babinski 1914 | Heilman 1998 | Anton 1899 | Ramachandran 1995")
    println("")

    let t1 = check_T1()
    if t1 { println("T1 PASS — normal bilateral monitoring (both sides Phi > 0)") } else { println("T1 FAIL") }

    let t2 = check_T2()
    if t2 { println("T2 PASS — R parietal lesion (contra-Phi drops, ipsi preserved, R>L asymmetry)") } else { println("T2 FAIL") }

    let t3 = check_T3()
    if t3 { println("T3 PASS — Anton's syndrome (confab MI > 0, veridical MI ~ 0)") } else { println("T3 FAIL") }

    let t4 = check_T4()
    if t4 { println("T4 PASS — confrontation therapy (monotonic Phi recovery)") } else { println("T4 FAIL") }

    let t5 = check_T5()
    if t5 { println("T5 PASS — determinism + latency < 5000 ms") } else { println("T5 FAIL") }

    println("")

    // Root cause comment: stage0 long && chains may mishandle short-circuit
    // ordering — use a mutable bool accumulator with sequential guards
    // (same idiom as other anima-engines).
    let mut all = true
    if !t1 { all = false }
    if !t2 { all = false }
    if !t3 { all = false }
    if !t4 { all = false }
    if !t5 { all = false }

    if all {
        println("[anosognosia_phi] 5/5 PASS — P96 DONE")
    } else {
        println("[anosognosia_phi] SOME FAILED")
    }
}

main()
